<section id="fs-id1845550" class="free-response">
<title>Critical Thinking Questions</title>
<exercise id="fs-id2181283">
<problem id="fs-id2801072"><para id="fs-id1612295">How does vasoconstriction help increase the core temperature of the body?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id2398066"><label/>
<para id="fs-id1758526">When blood flows to the outer layers of the skin or to the extremities, heat is lost to the environment by the mechanisms of conduction, convection, or radiation. This will cool the blood and the body. Vasoconstriction helps increase the core body temperature by preventing the flow of blood to the outer layer of the skin and outer parts of the extremities.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id2870043">
<problem id="fs-id1468939"><para id="fs-id1930328">How can the ingestion of food increase the body temperature?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id2022151"><label/>
<para id="fs-id2403190">The ingestion of food stimulates digestion and processing of the carbohydrates, proteins, and fats. This breakdown of food triggers glycolysis, the Krebs cycle, the electron transport chain, fatty acid oxidation, lipogenesis, and amino acid oxidation to produce energy. Heat is a byproduct of those reactions.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
